      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "3bcbd4e52c535930",
      "text": "The study of how policy is formulated and implemented within organisations - especially educational organisations appears to be one of the [[SET/BAD Examples]]"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "98b94c4d160c9d94",
      "text": "Maguire et al (2015) offer one example of this and provide background to some of the broader literature."
    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "id": "f322aba4fb3bb147",
      "text": "<h3>SET mindset</h3>"
    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "id": "886fe3af00a79b7e",
      "text": "Outlining how much of the work on policy implementation assumes a <strong>strategic</strong> mindset. citing Colebatch (2006a, p. 3)\"Government recognises problems and chooses of action to deal with them: these courses of action are 'policy'\" (p. 485)"
    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "id": "4d8d83ddaaae5b83",
      "text": "And the <strong>tree-like</strong> perspective is also evident (emphasis added) \"policy making at the legislative level is still characterised by instrumentality and <em>hierarchy</em>\" (p. 485). Citing Spillane (2006, p. 6) and his argument that conventional studies (emphasis added) \"conceive of the school as a somewhat <em>homogenous</em> and <em>decontextualised</em> organisation, an undifferentiated '<em>whole</em>' into which various policies are sliipped or filtered into place\" (p. 486)."
    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "id": "cd65544961fa64cb",
      "text": "Leading to the [[blame the implementer]] problem where \"very often implementation failure gets blamed on policy actors, who it is alleged, choose not to enact the policy reform or who ignore it\" (p. 486)"
    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "id": "f6255c2e59a5f456",
      "text": "<h3>BAD mindset</h3>"
    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "id": "ee38c6750dafb6ed",
      "text": "But <strong>bricolage</strong> is evident when attention is paid to it. Drawing on Spillane (2004, p. 7) \"policy actors 'use the lenses they have developed through experience to filter their awareness' and interpret these signals\" (p. 486). The way in which policy is read and responded to \"will be situated and contextualised\" (p. 486). The enactment of policy \"involves creative processes of interpretation and recontextualisation\" (p. 486).  Spillane (2004) is mentioned as having a notion of policy work as \"a 'sense-marking' process\" (p. 497)."
    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "id": "140cfac1436d6158",
      "text": "Thus policies are not <strong>established</strong> they are mutable and are changed as \"the space for 'interpretation' varies from policy to policy and sometimes, from person to person...Policies rarely tell you exactly what to do, they rarely dictate or determine practice, but some more than others narrow the range for imaginative responses\" (p. 486). There are variable affordances for change of policy. The idea of [[discretionary spaces]] from Fenwick & Edwards (2010, p. 126) is also mentioned as \"beyond policy, corners of the school where policy does not reach, bits of practice that are made up of teachers' good ideas or chance or simply the time of the year and the nature of the subject/discipline.\" (p. 497)"
    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "id": "8f8eef406d1e641f",
      "text": "And the <strong>distributed</strong> nature of the policy environment creates problems because most common school-based policy implementation studies \"do not illuminate the ways in which policies can be clustered together to form new policy ensembles that can have unintended, or unexpected consequences\" (p. 486)"
    },
